    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-03-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="835"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d835">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 847/227.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Weitzel</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-03-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 2, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 647.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to advise the department that
                    Dr. Carlos A. Mendoza, “segundo designado” Second Vice President of Panama, took
                    oath of office on March 1, 1910, at 3.45 p.m., as Chief Executive of the
                    Republic, in succession to Don Jose Domingo de Obalda, deceased.</p>
                <p>The ceremony was held in the supreme court room before the members of that
                    tribunal, the oath being administered by the chief justice, as shown by the
                    record of the proceedings, copy of which is transmitted herewith.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d835fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The induction into office was brief and simple, and was attended by about 30
                    persons, including myself.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George T. Weitzel.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
